<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="50" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="50">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="50">
This is a widespread genus found throughout the Palearctic and Afrotropical Regions. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kimsey" authorityYear="2011" class="Hexapoda" family="Tiphiidae" genus="Meria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="50">Meria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are sexually dimorphic, as are members of the genera 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kimsey" authorityYear="2011" class="Hexapoda" family="Tiphiidae" genus="Mesa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="50">Mesa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Guiglia" authorityYear="1959" class="Insecta" family="Tiphiidae" genus="Myzinella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="50">Myzinella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Males are elongate and slender with straight, cylindrical antennae. Females are heavy-bodied, with coiled antennae. Males also have the distinctive hook-like apical metasomal sternum (uncus) found in other myzinines. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kimsey" authorityYear="2011" class="Hexapoda" family="Tiphiidae" genus="Meria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="50">Meria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kimsey" authorityYear="2011" class="Hexapoda" family="Tiphiidae" genus="Mesa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="50">Mesa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Guiglia" authorityYear="1959" class="Insecta" family="Tiphiidae" genus="Myzinella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="50">Myzinella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the short, broad metasomal sternum I and petiolate forewing submarginal cell. Hosts are unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
